Yes, skip it for now.

Here's the honest breakdown of what actually matters for your portfolio as a backend engineer:

**What a recruiter will look at**
- Your schema design — how you modelled products, orders, carts, users
- Your auth implementation — JWT, email verification, token expiry
- Your order lifecycle — how a cart becomes an order, what happens after payment
- Your Stripe webhook handler — this alone shows you understand async, real-world backend patterns
- Your error handling — do your APIs return sensible errors or just 500s
- Your middleware — auth guards, role checks, input validation
- Your service layer — is business logic separated from controllers

**What they won't care much about**
- Whether you built an admin dashboard
- Whether the analytics charts look nice
- How many pages the frontend has

The dashboard is a frontend project wearing a backend hat. It's mostly `useQuery` calls and table rendering. There's almost no backend complexity in it beyond the analytics service, which you've already written.

**What to do instead**

When the main store backend is solid and tested, write a proper README. Document your API endpoints, your schema decisions, why you made certain choices — like prices in pence, product snapshots in cart items, webhook-first order creation. That documentation tells the backend story far better than a dashboard does.

Build the dashboard after you get a job, or if you genuinely have time and want to. But it is not what gets you hired.
